1.	The courses/faculty is quite good. You need to approach them if you need help, they will always do whatever they can to help you. I will say good repo with professor help you in the long run.  2.	Insurance charges vary greatly from what type of health insurance you take. It is approx. from $800-1600 per year. Groceries around $100-$150 monthly. Monthly rent also varies from $400-$800 where you stay. I have an apartment that I will be subletting let me know if you are interested. Here the monthly rent is $500 3.	From my perspective, I would say that location sometimes matters. Because here is DMV area most of the jobs are federal jobs i.e. they require some kind of security clearance. And as international students, we do not have that. So, certainly finding a job is not a piece of cake. But still, there are a few startups in the DMV area that might be willing to offer some roles to international students. 4.	If you want a career in the data analysis domain you can start working on your python, SQL, R, Tableau, etc. skills. Learn from online courses and then try doing passion projects which actually have some value and you can talk about it in an interview. Because if you don’t have experience directly related to the job you want a career in, it gets really difficult to land a job. So, it's important to have some projects to back you up. 5.	Literally very few people get jobs from career fairs. Most companies in UMD career fair do not provide sponsorship. And smith school has a different career fair where MS students can go. There are other career fairs which are better but you aren't allowed to go to those fairs. But as I said the number of people getting a job through fairs is really less. So, you are on your own to find a job. They have a career portal known as Hiresmith, which they will boost about in the orientation but there are very fewer job postings on that portal and most of the posting requires experience. 6.	Around 80-100

CONVERSATION TITLE: a 22,500% ROI opportunity, despite the recession?
CONTENT:
Hi Raghul,


You listed Financial Investing as one of your interests, so you surely know that in Internet-related IPOs one can make millions of dollars on a small investment. For example, Mike Walsh and Oren Michels earned $25M million each on their $5K investments in Uber. Such investment opportunities are rarely accessible to individual investors and investment banks and VC funds keep the best deals to themselves.


IT businesses can grow remarkably fast. Zoom has reached the valuation of $140B, TikTok - $75B, Salesforce - $225B.


At TransparentBusiness, we decided to open our Global Private Offering to individuals in order to create a large international network of "brand ambassadors" and prepare the company for a successful IPO next year. Here's the nature of the opportunity I offer for your consideration:


Four billion people have been ordered to stay home due to the coronavirus pandemic and executives around the world are discovering that managing remote workers blindly is as tricky as conducting an orchestra without seeing or hearing the musicians. Never before a market as large has appeared so fast.


We have a solution. It’s robust, acclaimed, and infinitely scalable. Designated by Citigroup as "the Top People Management Solution", our TransparentBusiness platform boosts the productivity of remote work by making it easy to monitor and coordinate. Our investors include current and former executives of Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, J.P. Morgan, Stifel, Bank of America, Barclays Global Investors, UBS, Wells Fargo, Goldman Sachs, Citigroup, Deutsche Bank, Microsoft, Telefonica, EY, Deloitte, IBM, LinkedIn, Microsoft and Accenture. Our objective is to make TransparentBusiness synonymous with the categories of Business Transparency and remote workforce management, globally.


The minimum investment is $5,000 and the maximum is $1M per person. The current stock price is $1 per share. As outlined in our kmgi.us/fs fundraising strategy summary, we plan to do a mini-IPO at the end of this year at $2 per share and the full-IPO on the New York Stock Exchange in the Fourth Quarter of the next year at $10 per share. At TransparentBusiness.com/invest you can review the detailed information about this opportunity and purchase our equity while this round remains open.


Looking forward to hearing from you,


With very best wishes,

Regardless of your engineering discipline – mechanical, architectural, welding, molding, casting, structural, civil – CAD drawings have a common purpose: to convey information on how a part, structure or assembly is to be produced. In order to enable production, you must have clear, precise drawings that are easy to interpret. In layman’s terms, drafting standards still matter. Modern design solutions have an arsenal of tools to create incredible drawings – automatic view creation, auto-dimensioning, parts-lists templates, title-block templates, section-view commands, auxiliary-view commands, tolerance analysis and more.

But the ease-of-use of these tools can cause the user to underestimate the technical knowledge needed to use them properly. Regardless of the software or technology used, even seemingly minor errors – an arrow pointing in the wrong direction or a misplaced view – can cause major issues in manufacturability. Detailed, accurate drawings are less likely to be misinterpreted, which means it is less likely they will cause the costly re-manufacture of parts.

Download the white paper today to learn techniques for streamlining the creation of production-ready CAD drawings.

Best,

Oliver Duncan

Product Manager of Solid Edge Design Products at Siemens PLM Software
